---
import BaseLayout from "../../layout/BaseLayout.astro";
import torchcorImage from "../../assets/images/torchcor.png";

const seo = {
	title: "TorchCor | CVD-Net Resources",
	description:
		"TorchCor is a Python library for GPU-accelerated simulation of cardiac electrophysiology, built on PyTorch.",
};
---

<BaseLayout seo={seo}>
	<div class="container mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-12">
		<div class="mb-12 text-center">
			<h1 class="mb-4 text-4xl font-bold lg:text-5xl">TorchCor</h1>
			<div class="mb-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2">
				<a
					href="https://github.com/sagebei/torchcor"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer"
				>
					<img
						src="https://img.shields.io/badge/GitHub-TorchCor-blue?logo=github"
						alt="GitHub Repository"
					/>
				</a>
				<a
					href="https://pypi.org/project/torchcor"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer"
				>
					<img
						src="https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/torchcor"
						alt="PyPI version"
					/>
				</a>
				<a
					href="https://pypi.org/project/torchcor"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer"
				>
					<img
						src="https://img.shields.io/pypi/pyversions/torchcor"
						alt="PyPI platforms"
					/>
				</a>
				<a
					href="https://arxiv.org/html/2510.12011v1"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer"
				>
					<img
						src="https://img.shields.io/badge/arXiv-2510.12011-b31b1b?logo=arxiv"
						alt="arXiv paper"
					/>
				</a>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="mb-10">
			<img
				src={torchcorImage.src}
				alt="TorchCor hero image"
				class="h-auto w-full rounded-lg shadow-md"
			/>
		</div>

		<div class="mx-auto">
			<p class="mb-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
				TorchCor is a Python library for simulating how electrical signals
				travel through the heart. These signals coordinate each heartbeat,
				and when they go wrong, dangerous rhythm disorders called
				arrhythmias can result. Simulating this process helps researchers
				and clinicians understand what causes these disorders and how to
				treat them — but traditionally, it has required access to expensive
				supercomputing clusters with many processors.
			</p>

			<p class="mb-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
				TorchCor removes this barrier by running simulations on GPUs
				(graphics processing units), the same type of hardware used in
				gaming and artificial intelligence. Built on top of PyTorch, a
				widely used machine learning framework, it can perform large-scale
				heart simulations on a single desktop workstation significantly
				faster than conventional CPU-based tools. This also makes it
				straightforward to combine traditional physics-based models with
				newer AI-driven approaches within a single environment. TorchCor
				has been rigorously verified against established solvers and
				benchmark problems and is freely available for academic and
				commercial use.
			</p>

			<h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-700">
				Getting Started
			</h2>
			<p class="mb-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
				TorchCor can be installed via pip:
			</p>
			<pre
				class="mb-6 rounded-md bg-slate-100 p-4 text-sm text-slate-800"><code>python -m pip install torchcor</code></pre>

			<p class="mb-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
				For more information, visit the
				<a
					href="https://github.com/sagebei/torchcor"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer">TorchCor GitHub repository</a
				> or read the
				<a
					href="https://arxiv.org/html/2510.12011v1"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer">accompanying paper on arXiv</a
				>.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
